questions.en_content:
Under the provisions of the Codes on Takeovers and Mergers and Share Repurchases, which of the following scenarios involve a mandatory offer obligation (assuming no additional exemptions apply)?

I. Mr. Ko is a high-net-worth individual who, through four transactions over the past three months, increased his voting rights in Company A from 27% to 32.5%;

II. Ms. Cheung, already a shareholder of Company C with 4% of the voting rights, inherited her father's estate in the past month, resulting in her holding 40% of the voting rights in Company C;

III. Corporation A is a subsidiary of Corporation B, and both corporations are shareholders of Corporation C, holding 16% and 6% of the voting rights, respectively. Corporation B recently purchased additional shares in the secondary market, increasing its voting rights from 6% to 15%;

IV. Ms. Yip and Mr. Lee are parties acting in concert, holding 10% and 25% of the voting rights in the listed corporation, Tai Cheung Shipping, respectively. Over the past month, Ms. Yip reduced her voting rights by 1.2%, while Mr. Lee increased his to 27.2% two days ago

questions.en_analysis:
Option I is an increase of more than 30%.

In Option II, the two parties are considered as persons acting in concert. For persons acting in concert, their shareholdings are to be viewed as a whole. For example, Miss Zhang and her father are to be regarded as a single entity. The transfer of shares occurs only within the persons acting in concert, and there is no overall increase. Therefore, the threshold of 2% has not been reached, and a mandatory offer can be exempted.

Option III involves persons acting in concert exceeding 30%. Option IV originally exceeded 30% but was less than 50%. However, within 12 months, the change exceeded 2% (a reduction of 1.2%, bringing the total to 25 + 10 - 1.2 = 33.8%; subsequently, an increase to (10 - 1.2) + 27.2 = 36% occurred. Calculating the lowest percentage within 12 months, the increase is (36 - 33.8) = 2.2%, which exceeds 2%).

A mandatory offer must be made under the following circumstances:

(a) When any person, whether through a series of transactions over a period or otherwise, acquires 30% or more of the voting rights of a company (see note below);

(b) When two or more persons acting in concert, who collectively hold less than 30% of the voting rights of a company, acquire additional voting rights, resulting in their collective holding reaching 30% or more of the voting rights of the company;

(c) When any person holding not less than 30% but not more than 50% of the voting rights of a company acquires additional voting rights, resulting in an increase of more than 2% in the percentage of voting rights held by that person, calculated based on the lowest percentage of voting rights held during the 12-month period up to and including the date of acquiring such voting rights;

or

(d) When two or more persons acting in concert, who collectively hold not less than 30% but not more than 50% of the voting rights of a company, acquire additional voting rights, resulting in an increase of more than 2% in their collective percentage of voting rights in the company, calculated based on the lowest percentage of voting rights held by them during the 12-month period up to and including the date of acquiring such voting rights

Note that the acceptance of benefits must be disclosed. Such disclosures can generally be included in client agreements or other investment management agreements, with the client's consent obtained.

This knowledge point is very important, and candidates must remember it. 【TT】

The regulations regarding the acceptance of non-monetary benefits include:

(a) Such items or services must be clearly beneficial to the clients of the licensed person or registered individual. The Securities and Futures Commission has provided a list of items and services it generally permits and does not permit.

(b) The execution of transactions must comply with the best execution requirements.

(c) The brokerage commission rate must not exceed the rate charged by a typical full-service brokerage.

(d) The client has provided written consent for the acceptance of such items or services, which may be included in the client agreement or other investment management agreement; and

(e) The licensed person or registered individual has disclosed the practice of accepting non-monetary benefits to the client. The disclosure must include details of the items and services received and must be provided to the client at least once a year.

Items and services permitted by the Securities and Futures Commission include:

(a) Research and advisory services;

(b) Economic and political analysis;

(c) Portfolio analysis (including valuation and performance measurement);

(d) Market analysis;

(e) Data and quotation services;

(f) Computer hardware and software related to the above items and services;

(g) Settlement and custodial services; and

(h) Investment-related publications.

Items and services not permitted by the Securities and Futures Commission include:

(a) Travel;

(b) Accommodation;

(c) Entertainment;

(d) General administrative items or services;

(e) General office equipment or premises;

(f) Membership fees;

(g) Employee compensation; and

(h) Direct monetary expenses

