Option II is incorrect; it should refer to the 'interests' in a collective investment scheme, not the 'returns'!

As for Option IV, this refers to options with futures contracts as the underlying, such as the Dow Jones Index options. (Teacher Shanhai expresses gratitude here for the reminder from student Dream).



Under Schedule 1 of the Securities and Futures Ordinance, the definition of 'securities' covers a wide range of instruments, including:

(a) Shares, stocks, debentures, loan stocks, funds, bonds, or notes;

(b) Rights, options, or interests in the above instruments;

(c) Certificates of interest or participation in the above instruments, or warrants to subscribe for or purchase the above instruments;

(d) Interests in a collective investment scheme;

(e) Interests, rights, or properties commonly known as securities, whether in the form of instruments or otherwise;

(f) Interests, rights, or properties prescribed by the Financial Secretary as securities under Section 392 of the Securities and Futures Ordinance; and

(g) Structured products not falling under paragraphs (a) to (f) but offered to the public, where such offers have been or are required to be authorized under Section 105(1) of the Securities and Futures Ordinance.

Note: According to the above definition, not all structured products are considered securities; only a portion of them are. For a discussion on what constitutes structured products and the circumstances under which they fall within the relevant definition, refer to Sections 8.3.27 to 8.3.31 of Chapter 8.

8.3 The above definition of securities specifically includes derivative instruments, such as options (and implied warrants) on underlying shares, securities, etc.

