Without the intervention in business operations item in IV, regarding non-delegable powers:

The study manual is as follows:

The Securities and Futures Ordinance stipulates that certain functions of the Securities and Futures Commission cannot be delegated to other bodies. These functions include the following powers:

(a) To make subsidiary legislation;

(b) To establish committees under Section 8 of the Securities and Futures Ordinance;

(c) To withdraw recognition of exchange companies;

(d) To appoint external investigators; and

(e) To initiate inquiry proceedings in the Market Misconduct Tribunal under Section 252(1) of the Securities and Futures Ordinance.

### Key points regarding intervention are as follows:

Part X grants the Securities and Futures Commission the power to intervene in the manner in which licensed corporations conduct their business. These powers:

(a) Safeguard the interests of investors of licensed corporations and minority shareholders of listed corporations, as well as protect the interests of persons and other creditors dealing with such corporations;

(b) May be exercised in accordance with the interests of the investing public or the public; and

(c) Are exercised when a licensed corporation exhibits the following circumstances:

(i) Demonstrates that it does not meet the fit and proper criteria;

(ii) Violates specified provisions of the Securities and Futures Ordinance;

(iii) Has its license suspended or revoked

