In any company, the primary objective of implementing good governance is to prevent management from placing their personal interests above the legitimate rights of the company and abusing their authority for personal gain. According to the general concepts outlined by the OECD, corporate governance can be enhanced through the following means:

(a) Establishing appropriate checks and balances, such as separating the roles of the chairman and the chief executive officer, appointing independent non-executive directors, forming an independent audit committee, and setting up a remuneration committee to oversee the compensation and benefits of directors and senior management;

(b) Increasing transparency and making disclosures to shareholders, stakeholders, and the public;

(c) Adopting international accounting and auditing standards;

(d) Establishing a robust protection framework for minority shareholders, creditors, and other lenders; and

(e) Identifying corporate misconduct and imposing penalties for such behavior

