Shanhai Teacher designed this question to test your understanding of authorization for discretionary accounts. However, many candidates mistakenly thought it was about "standing authorization." I say, can the trivial matter of giving your girlfriend a "standing authorization" to pay utility bills compare to someone handing over their salary card entirely to their spouse? 

**Discretionary Account**

A discretionary account is a client account where the client authorizes the licensed or registered person, or any individual employed by them (who must also be a licensed or registered person), to conduct transactions on behalf of the account without requiring prior approval from the client for each transaction. The client may grant full discretion or impose certain conditions (for example, requiring the licensed or registered person to conduct transactions only under specific restrictions).

The **Code of Conduct** imposes the following requirements for opening and operating discretionary accounts:

(a) The client must provide authorization in writing;  
(b) The authorization document should specify the individuals authorized to operate the account. If authorization is given to a person, the document must indicate that the person is an employee or agent of the licensed or registered person;  
(c) If the licensed or registered person or any individual employed by them is authorized to operate the account, they must explain the terms of the authorization to the client;  
(d) The licensed or registered person should confirm the authorization with the client annually. In this regard, the licensed or registered person may notify the client before the expiry date, stating that unless the client provides written notice of cancellation before the authorization expiry date, the authorization will be automatically renewed;  
(e) Such accounts should be designated as discretionary accounts;  
(f) The opening of a discretionary account must be approved by senior management;  
(g) The licensed or registered person must disclose in writing to the client, either at the account opening stage or before entering into a client agreement for the discretionary account, any benefits received when executing transactions for the client’s account—this includes any monetary gains under explicit remuneration arrangements and any other monetary or non-monetary benefits; and  
(h) Internal monitoring systems to ensure proper supervision of the account’s operations

