Corporation A is a licensed corporation in Hong Kong with a large number of clients and a strong reputation.

It has already obtained insurance coverage in accordance with the 'Securities and Futures (Insurance) Rules.' Under these rules, which of the following risks are covered?

I. Significant losses incurred by Corporation A due to substantial market fluctuations;

II. Fraudulent or dishonest acts committed by employees of Corporation A, its associated entities, or service departments;

III. Forgery of cheques or other negotiable instruments, or fraudulent alterations to cheques or other negotiable instruments;

IV. Substantial losses suffered by clients as a result of margin trading

questions.en_analysis:
The scope of insured risks refers to the risk of loss incurred by a licensed corporation's client assets (including assets received or held by an associated entity of the licensed corporation) due to fraud, theft, or other reasons.

Specified licensed corporations are required under this rule to purchase and maintain insurance coverage for risks arising from losses attributable to the following circumstances related to client assets received or held by the corporation in connection with regulated activities conducted in Hong Kong (including assets received or held by an associated entity of the corporation) —

(a) Fraudulent or dishonest acts committed by employees of the specified licensed corporation (or its associated entity or service unit);

(b) Robbery or theft incidents occurring while client assets are under the custody of the specified licensed corporation (or its associated entity);

(c) Forgery of cheques or other negotiable instruments, or fraudulent alteration of cheques or other negotiable instruments;

(d) Fraudulent use of information systems;

(e) Forgery of instructions related to client assets or issuance of fraudulent instructions concerning client assets

questions.en_content:
According to the requirements of the Internal Control Guidelines, which of the following are characteristics of a good division of responsibilities and functions?

I. The formulation of policies, supervision, monitoring, and internal audit functions should not be performed by staff responsible for frontline business operations;

II. Sales, trading, and settlement functions should be clearly separated;

III. The formulation of risk management policies and risk measurement should be separated;

IV. Where possible, monitoring and internal audit functions should be separated and independent from operational functions, and should report directly to senior management

According to the Internal Control Guidelines, what characteristics should good management and supervision possess for intermediaries?

I. Granting stock options to senior management so that they can receive a payment upon leaving their positions;

II. Regularly communicating with senior management regarding the intermediary's policies, procedures, operations, and financial condition;

III. Senior management should assume full responsibility for operations, including establishing and implementing internal control systems, ensuring their continuous effectiveness and compliance with the systems;

IV. Clearly defining authority for key positions, policies, and procedures to enable necessary delegation and communicating this throughout the business

questions.en_analysis:
I can be done, but it is not a 'characteristic' that good management and supervision should possess.

Management and Supervision

Purpose: The purpose is for senior management to establish and maintain an effective management and organizational structure to ensure that business operations are conducted in a sound, efficient, and effective manner.

Monitoring Guidelines

The characteristics of senior management's role within this structure include:

(a) Senior management should assume full responsibility for operations, including the formulation and implementation of internal monitoring systems, ensuring their ongoing effectiveness and compliance with these systems;

(b) Regularly communicate monitoring information related to the following with senior management at all levels:

(i) The firm's policies, procedures, operations, and financial condition;

(ii) Quality risks and identified weaknesses;

(iii) Any instances of non-compliance with laws and regulations; and

(iv) Any deviations from business objectives;

(c) Define clear reporting lines and assign supervisory and reporting responsibilities;

(d) Clearly define authority for key positions, policies, and procedures to enable necessary authorization and disseminate this information across all business areas; and

(e) Management and supervisory functions should be assigned to individuals with appropriate qualifications and extensive experience

